column15: In Northern Ireland:    Schools are to remain closed for an extended period as the Stormont executive agreed new measures this evening to tackle the spread of Covid-19.    Deputy First Minister Michelle O'Neill said pupils will not be returning to classrooms on Monday January 11 as was originally intended.    Northern Ireland's 3 universities- Queen's Belfast, Ulster, and St Mary's seem to have closed campuses- see Queen's twitter post with FAQs for 'when to return to campus', indicating this is not yet occurring.      https://web.archive.org/web/20210106133036/https://www.irishnews.com/news/northernirelandnews/2021/01/04/news/covid-19-schools-closed-for-extended-period-as-northern-ireland-in-dire-situation--2177581/    https://web.archive.org/web/20210106133241/https://www.nidirect.gov.uk/articles/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-schools-colleges-and-universities    https://web.archive.org/web/20210106134210/https://twitter.com/QUBelfast/status/1346562116497649664      In England: government guidance for universities is: 'Universities- Those students who are undertaking training and study for the specific courses should return to face to face learning as planned and be tested twice, upon arrival or self-isolate for ten days https://web.archive.org/web/20210106100514/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-lockdown-stay-at-home'. As our codebook describes, the C1 indicator records closing of schools and universities, so this does not close universities, and therefore does not warrant a 3 code.

Education closed for all devolved nations at all levels    England enters lockdown on Tuesday 5 January. All schools are closed, except for the children of essential workers, despite all students having attended school on Monday 4th.     Colleges, primary (reception onwards) and secondary schools will remain open for vulnerable children and the children of critical workers. All other children will learn remotely until February half term    Universities- Those students who are undertaking training and study for the specific courses should return to face to face learning as planned and be tested twice, upon arrival or self-isolate for ten days, best fit for universities is a 3 code due to widespread closure.      https://web.archive.org/web/20210106100514/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-lockdown-stay-at-home
column24: Non-essential businesses closed across all 4 devolved nations- 3G        Scots are to be ordered to stay at home amid a fresh Covid-19 lockdown on 5 January. These are the toughest restrictions Scotland has faced since the lockdown of March 2020.  Non essential workplaces closed and people must work from home if possible.    These rules will apply across the Scottish mainland until at least the end of January, and will be kept under review.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210104154939/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-55531069      England enters lockdown on Tuesday 5 January.       To reduce social contact, the regulations require some businesses to close and impose restrictions on how some businesses provide goods and services    https://web.archive.org/web/20210106100514/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-lockdown-stay-at-home    Wales has been in lockdown with the requirement to close non-essential businesses since 20 December:    All non-essential retail, close contact services, gyms and leisure centres and hospitality closed at "end of trading" on Saturday Dec 19.     http://web.archive.org/web/20201221233510/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/12/21/wales-lockdown-rules-travel-england-christmas-covid-when-end/    Northern Ireland closed nonessential businesses on 26 December:    From midnight 26 December Northern Ireland enters a national lockdown for 6 weeks. Non essential businesses must close (with a few exceptions, but dominant trend is closure of non-essential)      https://web.archive.org/web/20201224145053/https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/sites/default/files/publications/health/covid-regs-amdt-no-24.pdf
column60: All devolved nations are under stay at home orders    Scots are to be ordered to stay at home amid a fresh Covid-19 lockdown on 5 January. These are the toughest restrictions Scotland has faced since the lockdown of March 2020.      The new rules - which will be put down in law - mean Scots will only be allowed to leave home for essential purposes, such as shopping for food and medicine, exercise and caring responsibilities.    No limit is to be put on how many times people can go out to exercise, but outdoor meetings are to be limited to a maximum of two people from two households.      These rules will apply across the Scottish mainland until at least the end of January, and will be kept under review.    https://web.archive.org/web/20
column69: All four nations are under 'lockdown' restrictions which prevents travel in all four nations. While in Northern Ireland Apart from the stay at home requirement, other restrictions on travel remain guidance (not requirements), the dominant tendency seems to be that people cannot travel to other devolved nations, or within their nation, so coded as a 2G to represent dominant tendency    https://web.archive.org/web/20210106092408/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-54117810
column81: Chancellor announces one-off top up grants for retail, hospitality and leisure businesses worth up to £9,000 per property to help businesses through to the Spring, £594 million discretionary fund also made available to support other impacted businesses. The cash is provided on a per-property basis to support businesses through the latest restrictions, and is expected to benefit over 600,000 business properties, worth £4 billion in total across all nations of the UK.  GBP4.6b = USD6,265,344,302 (GBP1 = USD1.362031)  Link -  https://web.archive.org/web/20210112060711/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/46-billion-in-new-lockdown-grants-to-support-businesses-and-protect-jobs

column79: The government has quietly introduced a loophole to its eviction ban that waters down protections for people who lost their jobs during the pandemic.    Ministers on Friday announced that they were extending the ban on bailiff evictions that has been in place since the first lockdown in March, covering most tenants for another six weeks.    But the announcement did not mention a key change snuck out in legislation that will for the first time give landlords the power to evict people for not paying their rent during lockdown.      https://web.archive.org/web/20210115172832/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/eviction-ban-loophole-substantial-arrears-six-months-b1784836.html

column94: The UK has so far secured access to 367 million doses from 7 vaccine developers across 4 different formats (viral vectored vaccines, recombinant protein-based adjuvanted vaccines, whole inactivated viral vaccines and mRNA vaccines), with an expected cost of £2.9bn across the five final contracts signed to date. As announced in the Spending Review, the government has now made available more than £6bn in total to develop and procure COVID-19 vaccines.    Not coded amount as not clear that this is new spending and if so exactly how much,    https://web.archive.org/web/20210129112143/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-covid-19-vaccines-delivery-plan/uk-covid-19-vaccines-delivery-plan

column88: Current policy:   "Use this service to order a test if you have at least one of these 3 coronavirus (COVID-19) symptoms:    a high temperature  a new, continuous cough  you’ve lost your sense of smell or taste or it’s changed  You can also use this service if:    you’ve been asked to get a test by a local council  you’re taking part in a government pilot project  you’ve been asked to get a test to confirm a positive result  you’ve received an unclear result and were told to get a second test  you need to get a test for someone you live with who has symptoms  you’re in the National Tactical Response Group"    Source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20210208103235/http://www.gov.uk/get-coronavirus-test
column106: Current groups included: people aged 70 and over, people who are at high risk from coronavirus (clinically extremely vulnerable), people who live or work in care homes, health and social care workers    Source:   https://web.archive.org/web/20210209001617/https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/coronavirus-vaccination/coronavirus-vaccine/

column74: Announced Feb 9: "All travellers entering the UK will be required to take two coronavirus tests while quarantining in an attempt to prevent variants entering the country.  Arrivals will be required to get a test on days two and eight of their 10-day quarantine period, whether they are isolating at home or in a hotel."     http://web.archive.org/web/20210209111950/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-55989921
column106: Who is being vaccinated now?  Vaccines are given to the most vulnerable first. A list of high-priority groups - covering up to 99% of those most at risk of dying - is being followed.    If you're 70 or over in England and haven't yet been vaccinated, you are now being asked to contact the NHS to book an appointment online or by calling 119 free of charge.    Most NHS frontline staff, care home residents and workers, and over 75s have been vaccinated. Some areas are now inviting over 60s.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210210172706/https://www.bbc.com/news/health-55045639

column24: England: You may only leave your home for work if you cannot reasonably work from home, to help reduce the spread of the virus and protect others. If you cannot work from home you should continue to travel to your workplace. This includes, but is not limited to, people who work in: critical national infrastructure, construction, manufacturing, childcare or education, essential public services; essential retail, such as supermarkets and pharmacies.   https://web.archive.org/web/20210223022251/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-lockdown-stay-at-home  Scotland: Only essential retail will be able to remain open providing they follow and have implemented Scottish Government guidance to ensure the safety of customers and staff. If you are able to work from home, you must do so wherever possible. Under current rules you need to have a reasonable excuse for leaving the house.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210222193159/https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-stay-at-home-guidance/  NI: Close contact services are not permitted to operate. Only essential retail is permitted to remain open.   https://web.archive.org/web/20210223110027/https://www.nidirect.gov.uk/articles/coronavirus-covid-19-regulations-guidance-what-restrictions-mean-you  Wales: What must be closed at alert level 4: Leisure and fitness facilities, Hospitality (except for takeaway and delivery), Close contact services, Non-essential retail (click and collect allowed)  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223110255/https://gov.wales/alert-level-4-guide
column33: England: It is against the law to meet socially with family or friends unless they are part of your household or support bubble. You cannot leave home for recreational or leisure purposes  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223022251/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-lockdown-stay-at-home  Scotland: Stadia must be closed to spectators. No live events are permitted. All leisure and entertainment premises must be closed  https://web.archive.org/web/20210222193159/https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-stay-at-home-guidance/  NI: You may not organise, operate or take part in an indoor or outdoor gathering which consists of more than six people.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223110027/https://www.nidirect.gov.uk/articles/coronavirus-covid-19-regulations-guidance-what-restrictions-mean-you  Wales: At alert level 4 you must stay at home.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223110255/https://gov.wales/alert-level-4-guide
column42: England: It is against the law to meet socially with family or friends unless they are part of your household or support bubble.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223022251/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-lockdown-stay-at-home  Scotland: local outdoor informal exercise such as walking, cycling, golf, or running (in groups of up to 2 people, plus any children under 12, from no more than 2 households) is allowed.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210222193159/https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-stay-at-home-guidance/  NI: Up to six people (including children of all ages) from a maximum of two households can meet outdoors, or in non-domestic indoor settings for a permitted reason.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223110027/https://www.nidirect.gov.uk/articles/coronavirus-covid-19-regulations-guidance-what-restrictions-mean-you  Wales: Outdoor exercise with household, support bubble, or with people from one other household, as long as the total number of people exercising is no more than 4 is allowed  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223110255/https://gov.wales/alert-level-4-guide
column51: Temporary suspension of some National Rail operators in response to National Lockdown.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223112622/https://www.nationalrail.co.uk/service_disruptions/indicator.aspx
column60: England: You must not leave, or be outside of your home except where necessary. You may leave the home to: shop for basic necessities, go to work, exercise etc  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223022251/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-lockdown-stay-at-home  Scotland: By law, in a Level 4 area, you can only leave your home (or garden) for an essential purpose.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210222193159/https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-stay-at-home-guidance/  NI: You must not leave, or be outside of your home except where necessary. You may leave the home: to obtain goods or services from any business permitted to open, to take exercise, to visit your bubble, to visit hospital, GP, medical appointments or health services (including mental health) etc  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223110027/https://www.nidirect.gov.uk/articles/coronavirus-covid-19-regulations-guidance-what-restrictions-mean-you  Wales: At alert level 4 you must stay at home.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223110255/https://gov.wales/alert-level-4-guide
column69: England: If you need to travel you should stay local. This means you should avoid travelling outside of your village, town or the part of a city where you live. You should reduce the number of journeys you make overall.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223022251/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-lockdown-stay-at-home  Scotland: By law, you can only leave your home (or garden) if you have a reasonable excuse  https://web.archive.org/web/20210222193159/https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-stay-at-home-guidance/  NI: You must not leave your home unless you have a reasonable excuse (for example, for work or education purposes). You should not travel more than 10 miles from your home in order to take exercise.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223110027/https://www.nidirect.gov.uk/articles/coronavirus-covid-19-regulations-guidance-what-restrictions-mean-you  Wales: At alert level 4 you must not travel without reasonable excuse.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223110255/https://gov.wales/alert-level-4-guide
column74: You cannot currently enter the UK if you’ve been in or through a country on the banned travel list (sometimes known as the ‘red list’) in the last 10 days, unless you’re British, Irish or you have the right to live in the UK.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210217091929/https://www.gov.uk/uk-border-control?priority-taxon=774cee22-d896-44c1-a611-e3109cce8eae
column77: If your employer has less or no work for you because of coronavirus, they could get a Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme grant to help them to carry on paying you. This is known as being put ‘on furlough’ or ‘on flexible furlough’, and means that you’ll get at least 80% of your normal pay.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210218101527/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-what-to-do-if-youre-employed-and-cannot-work
column79: Mortgage payment holidays are extended until 31 March 2021. Lenders are extending the offer of payment holidays to people who are struggling to pay their mortgage because of coronavirus. You can apply for a payment holiday unless you've already had 6 months' of payment deferrals since March.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210127121002/https://england.shelter.org.uk/housing_advice/coronavirus  Other bill/mortgage deferral and benefits schemes are also available.  https://web.archive.org/web/20210223114256/https://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/debt-and-money/if-you-cant-pay-your-bills-because-of-coronavirus/

column81: People experiencing the longer-term effects of long COVID will benefit from £18.5 million to fund research projects to help better understand the causes, symptoms and treatment of the condition. column77: The UK Furlough Scheme, which supports individuals who cannot work due to their workplace being closed, is set to change from 1 July, though this does not affect people's wages.      The scheme allows employers to keep staff on the payroll but without them coming to work, with the Government paying 80 per cent of their salaries, up to a maximum cap of £2,500.    From 1 July, the Government has reduced its support from 80 per cent of employees’ wages to 70 per cent.    Employers will then have to top up the remaining 10 per cent, so staff still receive 80 per cent of their salaries.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210630172019/https://inews.co.uk/inews-lifestyle/work/furlough-when-end-hmrc-scheme-changes-july-2021-new-rules-how-long-finish-explained-1079553

column74: Changes to UK International arrivals lists on 5 Aug:    The UK government has today (5 August 2021) announced that arrivals from France to England will no longer need to quarantine if they are fully vaccinated.    The step aligns France with the rest of the amber list now that the proportion of beta variant cases has fallen, where those who are fully vaccinated with a vaccine authorised and administered in the UK, US or Europe do not need to quarantine when arriving in England.    This move also simplifies the system to 3 categories, as well as the green watchlist to give travellers notice where green status is at risk.    arrivals from France will no longer need to quarantine if they are fully vaccinated  Austria, Germany, Slovenia, Slovakia, Latvia, Romania and Norway to be added to the government’s green list for travel  India, Bahrain, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates (UAE) will also be moved from the red to the amber list  Georgia, Mexico, La Reunion and Mayotte added to the red list to safeguard domestic vaccine rollout    https://web.archive.org/web/20210806111415/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/international-travel-country-listings-update

column74: The UK is removing all countries from its red travel list, just weeks after reactivating the list in response to the new Omicron variant.    As of tomorrow, 15 December, people arriving from 11 African countries will no longer need to stay in one of the government-run quarantine hotels.    People currently in a UK quarantine hotel will also be allowed to leave early, as long as they do not test positive for COVID-19.    However all current testing requirements will remain in place, Transport Secretary Grant Shapps confirmed on Twitter this afternoon.    he UK recently updated its travel rules, stipulating that all arrivals must now show a negative pre-departure PCR or lateral flow test that was taken within 48 hours of arriving.    This is in addition to a day 2 PCR test, which both UK citizens and visitors must await the results of in isolation. The rules vary for unvaccinated travellers.    http://web.archive.org/web/20211215095343/https://www.euronews.com/travel/2021/12/14/uk-travel-all-countries-removed-from-the-uk-s-red-quarantine-list

column79: The government has quietly introduced a loophole to its eviction ban that waters down protections for people who lost their jobs during the pandemic. column115: Still protections in place so coded as a 2.    Hundreds of thousands of care home residents will be able to leave the buildings where they have been confined for more than a year without having to self-isolate on their return.    They will be allowed out for visits to gardens, parks and beaches from Tuesday without being forced to self-isolate upon their return.    The latest move to relax the restrictions on the estimated 420,000 people living in English care homes was announced as coronavirus rates continue to fall across the country. Almost 95 per cent of residents have received their first dose of the vaccine, while 71 per cent have been jabbed twice.    They remain forbidden for the moment to go out in groups or to meet more than one person at a time outdoors, although this restriction could be further loosened later this month.    Visits indoors, apart from to use toilet facilities, remain banned and people are urged to avoid taking public transport if possible. An exemption will be made for people who want to vote in person in next Thursday’s local elections.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210507094208/https://inews.co.uk/news/uk/freedom-thousands-elderly-care-home-residents-from-tuesday-visits-outside-restored-981020

column69: People living in 8 areas with high cases of the Indian Variant are recommended to reduce movement    If you’re in an area where the new COVID-19 variant is spreading  This new variant is sometimes referred to as the variant first identified in India. It is spreading fastest in:    Bedford Borough Council  Blackburn with Darwen Borough Council  Bolton Metropolitan Borough Council  Burnley Borough Council  Kirklees Council  Leicester City Council  London Borough of Hounslow  North Tyneside Council  The new COVID-19 variant spreads more easily from person to person. To help stop the spread, you should take particular caution when meeting anyone outside your household or support bubble.    In the areas listed above, wherever possible, you should try to:    meet outside rather than inside where possible  keep 2 metres apart from people that you don’t live with (unless you have formed a support bubble with them), this includes friends and family you don’t live with  minimise travel in and out of affected areas    https://web.archive.org/web/20210528115758/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/covid-19-coronavirus-restrictions-what-you-can-and-cannot-do    https://web.archive.org/web/20210528115831/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-57232728    Controversy over the way this was communicated:    "We woke up on Monday morning to find apparently that guidance had been in force on the government's website since Friday, telling us not to move in and out of affected areas but nobody had bothered to tell us," she said.    She said that "to treat us as an afterthought on a government website is to treat people's lives with absolute contempt."    https://web.archive.org/web/20210528115741/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-57246973

column74: Changes to UK International arrivals lists on 5 Aug:    The UK government has today (5 August 2021) announced that arrivals from France to England will no longer need to quarantine if they are fully vaccinated.    The step aligns France with the rest of the amber list now that the proportion of beta variant cases has fallen, where those who are fully vaccinated with a vaccine authorised and administered in the UK, US or Europe do not need to quarantine when arriving in England.    This move also simplifies the system to 3 categories, as well as the green watchlist to give travellers notice where green status is at risk.    arrivals from France will no longer need to quarantine if they are fully vaccinated  Austria, Germany, Slovenia, Slovakia, Latvia, Romania and Norway to be added to the government’s green list for travel  India, Bahrain, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates (UAE) will also be moved from the red to the amber list  Georgia, Mexico, La Reunion and Mayotte added to the red list to safeguard domestic vaccine rollout    https://web.archive.org/web/20210806111415/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/international-travel-country-listings-update

column121: 11/11/21 - 31/1/22/22  Law in effect on 11 November 2021- staff can only go into a care home if they are vaccinated.    From 22 July 2021 care home staff have 16 weeks to get vaccinated. Staff must have 1st dose by 16 September 2021. This gives them time to get a second dose by 11 November 2021.    https://archive.vn/vI1Es    http://web.archive.org/web/20220210123642/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/vaccination-of-people-working-or-deployed-in-care-homes-operational-guidance    31 January 2022    Since 11 November 2021, all care home workers, and anyone entering a care home, have needed to be fully vaccinated, unless they are exempt under the regulations.    As announced by the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care on 31 January 2022, the government has stated that its intention is to revoke the regulations making vaccines a condition of deployment for health and social care staff, subject to parliamentary process.    Legal requirement for health and social care staff to be double jabbed to be removed, subject to consultation and Parliamentary approval    http://web.archive.org/web/20220209045009/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/vaccination-of-people-working-or-deployed-in-care-homes-operational-guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-vaccination-of-people-working-or-deployed-in-care-homes-operational-guidance    http://web.archive.org/web/20220208144510/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/consultation-on-removing-vaccination-as-a-condition-of-deployment-for-health-and-social-care-staff    http://web.archive.org/web/20220210124238/https://www.nursingtimes.net/news/coronavirus/government-confirms-u-turn-on-mandatory-vaccination-policy-31-01-2022/

column74: 1/1/22 - 10/2/22 - 2/1  Fully vaccinated arrivals do not need to quarantine upon arrival, but must take a COVID-19 test within 48 hours upon arrival. Non-vaccinated arrivals must quarantine for 10 days, and must take a PCR test 48 hours prior to departure and then test upon arrival on days 2 and 8.These rules are set to change on 11 February.  As of 15 December 2021, there are no countries on the red list.   Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20220127010758/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/travel-to-england-from-another-country-during-coronavirus-covid-19#international-travel-rules-until-11-february-2022     Changes to be introduced 11 February for fully vaccinated travellers:    Mr Speaker, from 4am on the 11th February, and in time for the half-term break, eligible fully vaccinated passengers arriving in the UK will no longer have to take a post-arrival, lateral flow test.  Today I can announce that passengers who do not qualify as fully vaccinated will no longer be required to do a day 8 test after arrival or, indeed, to self-isolate. They will still need to fill out a passenger locator form to demonstrate proof of a negative COVID test taken 2 days before travel, and they must also take a post-arrival PCR test.  https://archive.vn/FNxIc

column115: Can I visit someone in hospital or a care home?    There are restrictions on hospital visits, with certain exceptions, such as a birthing partner supporting a woman during certain visits. column33: Domestic certificates were introduced on 29 November 2021 and will be enforceable from 13 December 2021.    Why you need a domestic certificate  Domestic certificates were introduced on 29 November and will be enforceable on 13 December 2021. This means that some hospitality venues will ask for evidence of your vaccination status.    Venues include:    nightclubs  hospitality venues which serve food and drink  cinemas, theatres, concert halls and conference centres  indoor events with 500 or more attendees with some or all of the audience not normally seated  outdoor events with 4,000 or more attendees with some or all of the audience not normally seated  events where more than 10,000 people will be present, regardless of whether they are seated    http://web.archive.org/web/20211215101228/https://www.nidirect.gov.uk/services/apply-domestic-covid-vaccination-certificate

column74: 1/1/22 - 10/2/22 - 2/1  Fully vaccinated arrivals do not need to quarantine upon arrival, but must take a COVID-19 test within 48 hours upon arrival. Non-vaccinated arrivals must quarantine for 10 days, and must take a PCR test 48 hours prior to departure and then test upon arrival on days 2 and 8.These rules are set to change on 11 February.  As of 15 December 2021, there are no countries on the red list.   Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20220127010758/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/travel-to-england-from-another-country-during-coronavirus-covid-19#international-travel-rules-until-11-february-2022     Changes to be introduced 11 February for fully vaccinated travellers:    Mr Speaker, from 4am on the 11th February, and in time for the half-term break, eligible fully vaccinated passengers arriving in the UK will no longer have to take a post-arrival, lateral flow test.  Today I can announce that passengers who do not qualify as fully vaccinated will no longer be required to do a day 8 test after arrival or, indeed, to self-isolate. They will still need to fill out a passenger locator form to demonstrate proof of a negative COVID test taken 2 days before travel, and they must also take a post-arrival PCR test.  https://archive.vn/FNxIc

column60: Scots are to be ordered to stay at home amid a fresh Covid-19 lockdown on 5 January. These are the toughest restrictions Scotland has faced since the lockdown of March 2020.      The new rules - which will be put down in law - mean Scots will only be allowed to leave home for essential purposes, such as shopping for food and medicine, exercise and caring responsibilities.    No limit is to be put on how many times people can go out to exercise, but outdoor meetings are to be limited to a maximum of two people from two households.      These rules will apply across the Scottish mainland until at least the end of January, and will be kept under review.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210104154939/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-55531069

column24: New lockdown rules:    1. Click and collect  The availability and operation of click and collect services will be limited to retailers selling essential items such as clothes, footwear, baby equipment, homeware and books. Also, outlets that sell electrical goods; do key cutting; undertake shoe repairs, plus garden centres and plant nurseries can continue the collect service.    For qualifying businesses, staggered appointments will need to be offered to avoid any potential for queuing, and access inside premises for collection will not be permitted.    Analysis: Business clicks but doesn’t collect  2. Takeaway services  Customers in Scotland will no longer be allowed to go inside to collect takeaway food or coffee. Businesses will have to operate from a serving hatch or doorway.    The aim is to reduce the risk of customers coming into contact indoors with each other, or with staff.    3. Alcohol consumption  It will be against the law in all level four areas of Scotland to drink alcohol outdoors in public.    This will mean that buying a takeaway pint and consuming on the street will not be permitted.    It is intended to underline the message that people should only be leaving home for essential purposes.      https://web.archive.org/web/20210115173223/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-55649853
column60: The Scottish government is strengthening the obligation on employers to allow their staff to work from home whenever possible.    The law already says that people should only be leaving home to go to work if it is work that cannot be done from home. This is a legal obligation that falls on individuals.    However, statutory guidance is being introduced to make clear that employers should support employees to work from home wherever possible.      https://web.archive.org/web/20210115173223/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-55649853

column33: From 17 May the majority of mainland Scotland, with the exception of Glasgow and Moray, will move to Level 2 of the Scottish Government’s Strategic Framework for COVID-19. At Level 2 - 100 people indoors, 250 outdoors where there is unrestricted standing and 500 for events with seating. As events are still not permitted in Glasgow City and Moray, the coding remains at a 2, with the T flag to show that this only applies to those areas.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210513172932/https://www.visitscotland.org/events/advice-materials/coronavirus
column42: In Glasgow City and Moray groups of up to six from six households can meet outdoors, but there is no indoor visits to private homes. In contrast, in all other areas of Scotland at Level 2, most areas have moved to this level which allows six people from three households to meet inside and stay overnight.     As the limit is still under 10, the coding remains at a G code.      https://web.archive.org/web/20210521095026/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-57076243    https://web.archive.org/web/20210521100057/https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-protection-levels/pages/protection-level-2/
column69: Most of Scotland moves to Level 2 on 17 May, except Glasgow City and Moray who remain at Level 3 due to high case numbers.    Travel around Scotland is permitted but you cannot enter somewhere with level three restrictions. In Glasgow City and Moray people should only travel in or out of the areas for permitted purposes. This means that the restrictions for C7 are now stricter than beforehand, despite increased freedoms in all Level 2 areas.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210521095026/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-57076243    https://web.archive.org/web/20210521100057/https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-protection-levels/pages/protection-level-2/

column24: MSPs voted to back the proposals, under which nightclubs and large events will only be able to allow entry to people who can show they have had two doses of a Covid vaccine.    The scheme is seen as a way of allowing events to go ahead despite surging cases of Covid-19, avoid re-imposing wider restrictions, and encouraging the uptake of the vaccine in younger people.    While the law came into effect from 1 October, it will not be formally enforced until 18 October to give venues time to test out their procedures.      https://web.archive.org/web/20211011105341/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-58422607

column42: People in Scotland have been asked to limit socialising to three households at a time in the run-up to Christmas amid concerns over the Omicron variant. The guidelines on social mixing will not be legally enforceable, but Ms Sturgeon warned: "Although it is guidance, please do not think of it as optional."    http://web.archive.org/web/20211215052621/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-59655829
column74: 1/1/22 - 10/2/22 - 2/1  Fully vaccinated arrivals do not need to quarantine upon arrival, but must take a COVID-19 test within 48 hours upon arrival. Non-vaccinated arrivals must quarantine for 10 days, and must take a PCR test 48 hours prior to departure and then test upon arrival on days 2 and 8.These rules are set to change on 11 February.  As of 15 December 2021, there are no countries on the red list.   Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20220127010758/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/travel-to-england-from-another-country-during-coronavirus-covid-19#international-travel-rules-until-11-february-2022     Changes to be introduced 11 February for fully vaccinated travellers:    Mr Speaker, from 4am on the 11th February, and in time for the half-term break, eligible fully vaccinated passengers arriving in the UK will no longer have to take a post-arrival, lateral flow test.  Today I can announce that passengers who do not qualify as fully vaccinated will no longer be required to do a day 8 test after arrival or, indeed, to self-isolate. They will still need to fill out a passenger locator form to demonstrate proof of a negative COVID test taken 2 days before travel, and they must also take a post-arrival PCR test.  https://archive.vn/FNxIc

from 27 December 2021, mandatory table service was reintroduced to venues serving alcohol for consumption on their premises  this means that you must be seated to consume any food or alcohol in a place that serves alcohol. No drinking at bar areas will be permitted  drinks may be served at bar areas but only where there is a clear queuing system with appropriate distancing and the drink consumed at a table  venues such as hospitality within theatres, which are unable to operate a table service, will be required to put in place an adequate queue management system which maintains physical distancing  the table service requirement will not apply at receptions associated with weddings, civil partnerships and funerals taking place within hospitality settings  from 27 December 2021, at least 1 metre physical mandatory distancing between groups is required, with a maximum of 3 households is recommended within any group attending together. This requirement also applies to any outdoor events held within hospitality settings. Appropriate table layout should be reintroduced to accommodate the 1 metre physical distancing requirement  from 27 December 2021, physical distancing in hospitality settings means that dancing will not be possible at most venues and premises. Receptions associated with weddings, civil partnerships and funerals will be exempt from that requirement. Please refer to the hospitality and tourism sector specific guidance, for further information  Information on business support available.  Nightclubs	  from 27 December 2021, nightclubs are required to close to members of the public unless the premises is repurposed as a pub, following the guidance for hospitality premises. Local licensing laws will apply    http://web.archive.org/web/20220110171005/https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-general-guidance-for-safer-workplaces/pages/sector-specific-measures/

column115: Some restrictions still in place in elderly care homes following 7 August but much less stringent than previous policy.    Version 10 of the guidance supersedes previous versions. The key changes are:    To introduce ‘essential visitors’. Each resident can now nominate an essential visitor. The essential visitor may visit the resident regularly indoors during a COVID-19 outbreak at the care home provided the resident or visitor do not themselves have COVID-19 (unless there are exceptional circumstances). This will ensure that people can continue to benefit from regular visits by a nominated essential visitor when wider restrictions on routine visits maybe in place.      To remove the limit of two indoor visitors at the same time per resident. This will now be subject to a risk assessment by the care home.  To remove the need for visitors to wear face coverings in outdoor areas of the care home.   To amend requirements on use of face coverings in indoor areas.   To clarify that indoor visits can take place in residents’ rooms as well as in a designated visiting space.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210811111305/https://gov.wales/visits-care-homes-guidance-providers-html

column24: People in Wales now need an NHS Covid pass to legally enter nightclubs and large events.    Anyone aged over 18 will be required to show the pass to prove they are either fully vaccinated or have had a negative lateral flow test result within the last 48 hours.    The new rule came into effect on 11 October.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211011105950/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-politics-58600373

column121: 11/11/21 - 31/1/22/22  Law in effect on 11 November 2021- staff can only go into a care home if they are vaccinated.    From 22 July 2021 care home staff have 16 weeks to get vaccinated. Staff must have 1st dose by 16 September 2021. This gives them time to get a second dose by 11 November 2021.    https://archive.vn/vI1Es    http://web.archive.org/web/20220210123642/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/vaccination-of-people-working-or-deployed-in-care-homes-operational-guidance

column74: 1/1/22 - 10/2/22 - 2/1  Fully vaccinated arrivals do not need to quarantine upon arrival, but must take a COVID-19 test within 48 hours upon arrival. Non-vaccinated arrivals must quarantine for 10 days, and must take a PCR test 48 hours prior to departure and then test upon arrival on days 2 and 8.These rules are set to change on 11 February.  As of 15 December 2021, there are no countries on the red list.   Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20220127010758/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/travel-to-england-from-another-country-during-coronavirus-covid-19#international-travel-rules-until-11-february-2022     Changes to be introduced 11 February for fully vaccinated travellers:    Mr Speaker, from 4am on the 11th February, and in time for the half-term break, eligible fully vaccinated passengers arriving in the UK will no longer have to take a post-arrival, lateral flow test.  Today I can announce that passengers who do not qualify as fully vaccinated will no longer be required to do a day 8 test after arrival or, indeed, to self-isolate. They will still need to fill out a passenger locator form to demonstrate proof of a negative COVID test taken 2 days before travel, and they must also take a post-arrival PCR test.  https://archive.vn/FNxIc

column24: Wales at Level 2 from 26 December 2021    Groups of no more than six people will be allowed to meet in pubs, cinemas and restaurants in Wales from 26 December, when the two metre social distancing rule will also return to public places and offices.    Measures will be put in place to protect customers and staff, such as one-way systems and barriers.    Fans will be banned from all sporting events in Wales from 26 December.    Nightclubs, originally planned to close on 27 December, will now shut a day earlier.    Face masks are still required in most public places, including buses, shops and hospitals.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220110171738/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-55333756

column115: Care homes could ban visits due to the rapid spread of the Omicron variant, however, no official guidance has been issued.    For now, the current rules apply.
